---
/**
 * Problem/Solution Guide: Academic and Researcher Insurance
 *
 * Health insurance for professors, researchers, postdocs, and academics working internationally.
 */

import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for Expat Academics and Researchers: Coverage for International Scholars";
const description = "Academic positions abroad have unique insurance challenges—short contracts, sabbaticals, research travel, and moving between institutions. Learn how professors, postdocs, and researchers can secure appropriate health coverage for their international academic careers.";

const tocItems = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Academic Insurance Challenges" },
  { id: "position-types", label: "Position Types" },
  { id: "university-coverage", label: "University Coverage" },
  { id: "gaps-transitions", label: "Gaps and Transitions" },
  { id: "research-travel", label: "Research Travel" },
  { id: "sabbaticals", label: "Sabbatical Coverage" },
  { id: "family-considerations", label: "Family Considerations" },
  { id: "cost-strategies", label: "Cost Strategies" },
  { id: "faq", label: "FAQs" },
];

const positionColumns = [
  { key: 'position', header: 'Position Type' },
  { key: 'typical_coverage', header: 'Typical Coverage' },
  { key: 'gaps_to_watch', header: 'Common Gaps' },
  { key: 'strategy', header: 'Recommended Strategy' },
];

const positionRows = [
  { position: 'Tenured professor', typical_coverage: 'University group plan', gaps_to_watch: 'Sabbaticals, international travel', strategy: 'Verify travel coverage, sabbatical provisions' },
  { position: 'Visiting professor', typical_coverage: 'Varies widely', gaps_to_watch: 'Short contracts, return home', strategy: 'Negotiate coverage or arrange personal policy' },
  { position: 'Postdoctoral researcher', typical_coverage: 'Often limited university plan', gaps_to_watch: 'Contract gaps, fellowship periods', strategy: 'Personal policy for continuity' },
  { position: 'Research fellow', typical_coverage: 'Grant-dependent', gaps_to_watch: 'Grant ending, funding gaps', strategy: 'Plan beyond current funding' },
  { position: 'Adjunct/part-time', typical_coverage: 'Often none', gaps_to_watch: 'No institutional coverage', strategy: 'Must arrange own coverage' },
  { position: 'PhD student abroad', typical_coverage: 'Student health plan', gaps_to_watch: 'Fieldwork, dissertation writing', strategy: 'Supplement for fieldwork travel' },
];

const countryColumns = [
  { key: 'country', header: 'Country' },
  { key: 'academic_coverage', header: 'Academic Employee Coverage' },
  { key: 'key_notes', header: 'Key Notes' },
];

const countryRows = [
  { country: 'United States', academic_coverage: 'University group plan (quality varies)', key_notes: 'COBRA for gaps, ACA marketplace backup' },
  { country: 'United Kingdom', academic_coverage: 'NHS + university supplement', key_notes: 'IHS required for visa holders' },
  { country: 'Germany', academic_coverage: 'Public (GKV) or private insurance', key_notes: 'Academics often eligible for private' },
  { country: 'France', academic_coverage: 'Sécurité Sociale automatic', key_notes: 'CNRS/INSERM have specific provisions' },
  { country: 'Australia', academic_coverage: 'Medicare for permanent, OSHC for visa holders', key_notes: 'Visa type determines access' },
  { country: 'Singapore', academic_coverage: 'University plan usually excellent', key_notes: 'NUS, NTU provide comprehensive coverage' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline="Insurance for Expat Academics and Researchers"
  subheadline="You've landed a postdoc position in Germany. A visiting professorship in Singapore. A research fellowship with fieldwork across three continents. Academic careers are increasingly international—but so are the health insurance challenges. Here's how professors, researchers, and scholars navigate coverage across institutions, countries, and career stages."
  canonicalPath="/guides/academic-researcher-insurance"
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose max-w-none">

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <p class="lead">
      Academic life is mobile by nature. You follow positions, grants, and research opportunities wherever they lead. A postdoc here, a visiting position there, sabbaticals and conferences around the world. This mobility creates extraordinary intellectual experiences—and complicated health insurance situations.
    </p>

    <p>
      University coverage varies dramatically by institution, country, and position type. Short contracts mean frequent transitions. Research travel takes you to places your insurance may not cover. Sabbaticals can suspend or complicate your home institution coverage. And through it all, you're trying to focus on your research, not insurance paperwork.
    </p>

    <p>
      This guide addresses the unique insurance challenges facing international academics. Whether you're a tenured professor taking a sabbatical abroad, a postdoc moving between institutions, or a researcher with fieldwork in remote locations, understanding your options helps you stay protected while pursuing your scholarly work.
    </p>

    <!-- Academic Insurance Challenges -->
    <section id="overview">
      <h2>Academic Insurance Challenges</h2>

      <h3>The Mobility Factor</h3>
      <p>
        Academic careers are defined by mobility. Early-career researchers move between postdoc positions, often in different countries. Mid-career academics take sabbaticals, visiting positions, and research leaves. Senior scholars travel for conferences, collaborations, and extended research visits. Each move creates insurance considerations.
      </p>

      <p>
        Unlike corporate employees who might relocate once for an international assignment, academics may change institutions, countries, and visa statuses multiple times throughout their careers. Insurance strategies must accommodate this ongoing mobility, not just single transitions.
      </p>

      <h3>Contract-Based Employment</h3>
      <p>
        Many academic positions are fixed-term. Postdocs are typically one to three years. Visiting positions may be one semester or one year. Research fellowships depend on grant duration. When contracts end, so does institutional coverage—often without the notice periods or transition support that permanent employees receive.
      </p>

      <p>
        The gap between contracts is particularly challenging. You may have a new position lined up, but it doesn't start for three months. During that gap, you need coverage. Planning for these transitions is essential for academics on contract-based positions.
      </p>

      <h3>Grant-Dependent Funding</h3>
      <p>
        Research fellowships and grant-funded positions create additional uncertainty. Grants may include health insurance funding—or may not. Grant extensions aren't guaranteed. Funding transitions can create coverage gaps that aren't anyone's responsibility to fill except your own.
      </p>

      <p>
        Understanding whether your grant covers insurance, for how long, and what happens when the grant ends should be part of your grant acceptance process—not a surprise discovery when funding runs out.
      </p>

      <h3>Multi-Country Research</h3>
      <p>
        Research often requires travel—fieldwork sites, archives, collaborating institutions, conferences. Your university coverage may be designed for the campus location, not for months of research in another country. Ensuring coverage follows your research activities requires attention.
      </p>

      <p>
        The nature of academic travel varies widely. A week at a conference differs from three months of fieldwork in a remote location. Insurance needs scale with travel duration, destination, and activities. One-size-fits-all coverage rarely addresses all academic travel scenarios.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Position Types -->
    <section id="position-types">
      <h2>Coverage by Position Type</h2>

      <ComparisonTable columns={positionColumns} rows={positionRows} />

      <h3>Tenured and Tenure-Track Faculty</h3>
      <p>
        Permanent faculty typically have the best institutional coverage—comprehensive university health plans, often with family coverage available. The main concerns are international travel coverage, sabbatical provisions, and what happens during research leaves. These positions provide stability, but the coverage isn't always designed for internationally mobile scholars.
      </p>

      <p>
        Review your university plan's provisions for extended international stays. Sabbaticals, research leaves, and visiting positions at other institutions may or may not be covered. Don't assume—check the policy language and ask HR specifically about your planned activities.
      </p>

      <h3>Visiting Professors and Scholars</h3>
      <p>
        Visiting positions vary enormously in coverage. Some institutions extend full benefits to visiting faculty; others provide minimal or no coverage. The host institution may expect you to maintain coverage from your home institution. Or you may fall between both and have inadequate coverage from either.
      </p>

      <p>
        Negotiate coverage as part of visiting position offers. If the host institution won't provide coverage, ensure your home institution coverage extends (and at what level). If neither covers you, factor the cost of personal international health insurance into your decision.
      </p>

      <h3>Postdoctoral Researchers</h3>
      <p>
        Postdocs often have less comprehensive coverage than faculty, despite similar work. Some universities include postdocs in faculty health plans; others provide separate, more limited postdoc coverage. And postdocs move frequently—two years here, three years there—creating repeated transitions.
      </p>

      <p>
        For postdocs planning international careers, personal international health insurance alongside or instead of institutional coverage provides continuity. You carry the same coverage from one position to the next, eliminating gaps and pre-existing condition concerns that arise with new employer coverage.
      </p>

      <h3>Research Fellows and Grant Recipients</h3>
      <p>
        Fellowship coverage depends entirely on how the grant is structured. Some fellowships include generous health benefits; others provide stipends that don't cover insurance. Some require you to remain affiliated with an institution (and its coverage); others leave you independent and responsible for your own insurance.
      </p>

      <p>
        Read fellowship terms carefully before accepting. If health insurance isn't covered, you need to budget for it—potentially $5,000-$15,000 annually for good international coverage. This significantly affects the real value of the fellowship.
      </p>

      <h3>Adjunct and Part-Time Academics</h3>
      <p>
        Adjunct faculty and part-time instructors often receive no benefits, including no health insurance. If you're piecing together adjunct positions internationally, you're entirely responsible for your own coverage. This is an overlooked cost of the adjunct academic path.
      </p>

      <p>
        Without institutional coverage, adjunct academics need personal health insurance. International health insurance may actually be more cost-effective than trying to navigate different national systems in each country where you teach.
      </p>

      <h3>PhD Students Abroad</h3>
      <p>
        PhD students typically have student health insurance, but this may not cover fieldwork in other countries, conference travel, or research visits. Dissertation research often requires extended time away from the home institution. Student coverage may be suspended or inadequate during these periods.
      </p>

      <p>
        Understand your student coverage limits before planning fieldwork. Supplementary travel insurance or international coverage for fieldwork periods protects you when student coverage doesn't extend.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- University Coverage -->
    <section id="university-coverage">
      <h2>Understanding University Coverage</h2>

      <ComparisonTable columns={countryColumns} rows={countryRows} />

      <h3>What University Plans Typically Cover</h3>
      <p>
        University health plans in most countries provide comprehensive coverage at the institution's location. Medical visits, hospitalization, prescriptions, mental health—the basics are usually covered for employees at their workplace location. Family coverage is often available, though sometimes at additional cost.
      </p>

      <p>
        Where university plans often fall short: international travel coverage, coverage during leaves, and continuity between positions. These are precisely the situations academics face regularly. Understanding what's covered and what isn't shapes your supplementary insurance needs.
      </p>

      <h3>International Travel Under University Plans</h3>
      <p>
        Many university plans provide some international travel coverage—often emergency coverage during short trips. But academic travel often exceeds these limits: a month of archival research, a semester of fieldwork, extended conference circuits. Check specific limits on trip duration, total days abroad annually, and what activities are covered.
      </p>

      <p>
        Even when international travel is covered, the level of coverage may be reduced—emergency only, limited networks, higher out-of-pocket costs. For extended or remote research, supplementary international coverage may be necessary even if you have a university plan.
      </p>

      <h3>Leaves of Absence</h3>
      <p>
        What happens to your university coverage during sabbatical, research leave, or unpaid leave? Policies vary. Some continue coverage unchanged. Others offer continuation at your expense. Some suspend coverage entirely during extended leaves. Know your policy before taking leave.
      </p>

      <p>
        Unpaid leaves are particularly risky—institutions may not continue coverage when you're not on payroll. Even paid sabbaticals may have different coverage terms than regular employment. Clarify the specific provisions for your planned leave.
      </p>

      <h3>Dependent and Family Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        If your family accompanies you internationally, are they covered? University plans typically cover dependents at the home location. Coverage when you're abroad for extended periods—and your family is with you—may be different. Verify dependent coverage for your specific situation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some universities offer separate travel policies for dependent coverage during international assignments. Others expect you to arrange family coverage independently. Don't assume your dependents are covered just because you are.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA Box -->
    <CTABox
      variant="highlight"
      title="Find Coverage for Your Academic Career"
      description="Compare international health insurance options designed for the mobility and transitions of academic life."
      buttonText="Compare Plans"
      buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    />

    <!-- Gaps and Transitions -->
    <section id="gaps-transitions">
      <h2>Managing Gaps and Transitions</h2>

      <h3>Between Positions</h3>
      <p>
        The gap between academic positions—your postdoc ended in June, your new position starts in September—is a common coverage challenge. Your old employer coverage ends; your new coverage hasn't started. Three months without insurance is risky.
      </p>

      <p>
        Options for gap coverage include: COBRA-style continuation (expensive but comprehensive), travel medical insurance (limited but affordable), short-term health insurance (varies by country), or international health insurance maintained throughout transitions (consistent but requires planning).
      </p>

      <h3>Country Transitions</h3>
      <p>
        Moving between countries adds complexity. Your coverage in one country doesn't transfer to another. You may need to navigate both leaving one health system and entering another, with potential gaps during the transition. International health insurance that works across countries simplifies these moves.
      </p>

      <p>
        Pre-existing conditions are a particular concern. Conditions documented under one policy may face waiting periods or exclusions under a new policy in a new country. Maintaining continuous coverage—even if changing policies—helps establish treatment history.
      </p>

      <h3>Waiting Periods</h3>
      <p>
        New employer coverage often has waiting periods—30 to 90 days before coverage begins. For academics starting new positions, this means weeks without institutional coverage. Bridge coverage for waiting periods protects you during this vulnerable time.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some countries' public health systems also have waiting periods for new residents. Canada, Australia, and others may require months of residency before public coverage applies. Private coverage during these waiting periods is essential.
      </p>

      <h3>Continuous Coverage Strategy</h3>
      <p>
        For academics who move frequently, maintaining personal international health insurance throughout your career provides continuity. You're always covered, regardless of position, institution, or country. When institutional coverage is available, your personal coverage becomes supplementary or secondary.
      </p>

      <p>
        This approach costs more than relying solely on institutional coverage, but eliminates gaps, pre-existing condition concerns, and transition stress. For career-long academic mobility, the continuity may be worth the investment.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Research Travel -->
    <section id="research-travel">
      <h2>Coverage for Research Travel</h2>

      <h3>Fieldwork in Remote Locations</h3>
      <p>
        Anthropological fieldwork, archaeological digs, ecological research—academic work often takes researchers to remote locations with limited healthcare infrastructure. Standard university or international coverage may be inadequate. You need coverage that includes medical evacuation, access to care in remote areas, and potentially adventure activity coverage.
      </p>

      <p>
        Evaluate fieldwork locations specifically. What healthcare is available? How far to the nearest adequate hospital? What evacuation options exist? Your insurance should match the actual risks and logistics of your research location.
      </p>

      <h3>High-Risk Research Environments</h3>
      <p>
        Some academic research takes scholars to conflict zones, politically unstable regions, or areas with significant health risks. Standard insurance may exclude these locations or situations. Specialized coverage for high-risk environments—security evacuation, kidnap and ransom, enhanced medical coverage—may be necessary.
      </p>

      <p>
        Universities often have risk management offices that can advise on coverage for dangerous research locations. They may have institutional policies or approved insurers for high-risk destinations. Consult with them before arranging travel.
      </p>

      <h3>Conference and Collaboration Travel</h3>
      <p>
        Regular academic travel—conferences, visiting other institutions, short research trips—is lower risk but still requires coverage. Your university plan's travel provisions usually handle this, but verify coverage levels, claim procedures, and any per-trip duration limits.
      </p>

      <p>
        Frequent travelers may find that individual trip limits aggregate across the year. If your plan covers 30-day trips but limits total foreign coverage to 90 days annually, a heavy conference schedule could exceed limits. Know the aggregate caps.
      </p>

      <h3>Multi-Site Research Projects</h3>
      <p>
        Research projects spanning multiple countries—interviews in six capitals, data collection across a region—require coverage that works everywhere you're going. Some locations may be specifically excluded from standard policies. Verify coverage for each country in your research plan.
      </p>

      <p>
        For extended multi-site research, international health insurance with worldwide coverage is often simpler than arranging separate coverage for each location. One policy, one set of documentation, consistent coverage throughout.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Sabbaticals -->
    <section id="sabbaticals">
      <h2>Sabbatical Coverage</h2>

      <h3>Understanding Your University's Sabbatical Policy</h3>
      <p>
        Sabbatical insurance policies vary by institution. Some continue full benefits throughout the sabbatical, whether you're on campus or abroad. Others modify coverage during sabbatical—perhaps continuing health insurance but with limited international provisions. Still others require you to arrange your own coverage during sabbatical leaves.
      </p>

      <p>
        Request your university's sabbatical policy documentation well before your sabbatical begins. Understand exactly what's covered, what limitations apply, and whether coverage differs based on your sabbatical location. Plan accordingly.
      </p>

      <h3>Domestic vs. International Sabbaticals</h3>
      <p>
        Spending your sabbatical at another institution in your home country usually means continued coverage under your university plan with minimal complications. International sabbaticals are different—your plan may not cover you adequately abroad, and the host institution may not cover you as a visitor.
      </p>

      <p>
        International sabbaticals often require supplementary coverage. International health insurance for the sabbatical period fills gaps in your university coverage. Some scholars maintain this coverage as primary during international sabbaticals, using university coverage as backup.
      </p>

      <h3>Sabbaticals With Family</h3>
      <p>
        Bringing your family on sabbatical adds complexity. Your dependents' coverage may not extend internationally, or may provide only emergency coverage abroad. Children's schooling and healthcare needs continue; elderly dependents may have specific medical requirements. Plan family coverage specifically for international sabbaticals.
      </p>

      <p>
        Family international health insurance policies or adding family to your international coverage ensures everyone is protected. This is particularly important for sabbaticals in countries where you won't have easy access to your usual healthcare providers.
      </p>

      <h3>Sabbatical in a Country With Public Healthcare</h3>
      <p>
        Taking sabbatical in a country with universal healthcare (UK, Canada, Germany) doesn't necessarily mean you'll have access to it. Public healthcare access typically requires residency status, which a visiting scholar may not have. Don't assume public healthcare access; verify your eligibility based on your visa status.
      </p>

      <p>
        Even with public healthcare access, you may want supplementary coverage—faster access, broader provider choice, coverage for services the public system doesn't include. International health insurance provides this regardless of host country public system provisions.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Family Considerations -->
    <section id="family-considerations">
      <h2>Family Coverage Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Dual-Academic Couples</h3>
      <p>
        When both partners are academics, coverage becomes complicated. Each may have their own institutional coverage. One may have coverage, the other not (if positions don't align). Moving together to new positions requires coordinating two people's coverage transitions. International moves may affect each partner's coverage differently.
      </p>

      <p>
        Consider whether one partner's coverage can serve the family while the other is between positions. Family plans that cover both partners regardless of individual employment status provide stability through career transitions.
      </p>

      <h3>Children and International Moves</h3>
      <p>
        Children's healthcare needs continue regardless of your academic mobility. Pediatric care, vaccinations, school requirements—all need coverage wherever you are. Moving internationally means finding new pediatric providers, potentially navigating care in another language, and ensuring coverage applies.
      </p>

      <p>
        For families moving frequently, maintaining consistent pediatric records and coverage helps. International health insurance with worldwide pediatric coverage means you don't restart with a new insurance system at each position change.
      </p>

      <h3>Trailing Spouse Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        When one partner's career drives moves, the trailing spouse's coverage may be inconsistent. They may be covered as a dependent on your plan—but if your coverage is institutional and changes with each position, their coverage is equally unstable. Independent coverage for trailing spouses provides consistency.
      </p>

      <p>
        Consider what happens if the trailing spouse takes employment abroad. They may then have their own coverage, creating coordination questions. Or they may lose dependent status on your plan. Plan for various scenarios as careers evolve.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Cost Strategies -->
    <section id="cost-strategies">
      <h2>Cost Strategies for Academics</h2>

      <h3>Maximizing Institutional Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        When institutional coverage is available, use it. University group plans are typically comprehensive and subsidized. Your cost is usually much lower than equivalent individual coverage. The strategy is to maximize institutional coverage when you have it, and efficiently bridge gaps when you don't.
      </p>

      <p>
        Understand your institutional coverage thoroughly. Use all the benefits available—preventive care, vision and dental if included, travel provisions. This maximizes value and reduces out-of-pocket costs during covered periods.
      </p>

      <h3>Strategic Gap Coverage</h3>
      <p>
        For gaps between positions, match coverage to duration and risk. A two-week gap might be covered by travel insurance. A three-month gap needs proper short-term or international health insurance. A year between positions requires comprehensive coverage.
      </p>

      <p>
        Consider your specific situation during gaps. Are you healthy with low expected healthcare needs? Are you managing a chronic condition requiring continuous care? Does your gap involve international travel? Match coverage level to actual needs during the gap period.
      </p>

      <h3>Grant Funding for Insurance</h3>
      <p>
        When applying for research grants, include insurance costs where allowed. Many funders recognize that researcher health coverage is a legitimate project expense. Including insurance in your grant budget means you're funded for coverage during the research period.
      </p>

      <p>
        Review funder guidelines for what insurance costs are allowable. Some cover full health insurance; others cover only research travel insurance. Maximize what you can include, and budget for what you can't.
      </p>

      <h3>Tax Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        Health insurance premiums may be tax-deductible depending on your country and employment situation. Self-employed researchers can often deduct premiums. Employees may have pre-tax premium options. Understanding tax treatment reduces the effective cost of coverage.
      </p>

      <p>
        Consult with a tax professional familiar with academic and international employment. The intersection of academic positions, international income, and health insurance creates complex tax situations. Professional advice helps you optimize.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Does my university health plan cover international research travel?</h3>
      <p>
        Most university plans include some international travel coverage, typically for short trips with emergency coverage. Extended research travel, fieldwork, and remote locations may exceed what's covered. Check your specific plan for trip duration limits, geographic restrictions, and activity exclusions.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I handle insurance between postdoc positions?</h3>
      <p>
        Options include COBRA continuation from your previous position (if available), short-term health insurance for the gap period, travel medical insurance if you'll be traveling, or maintaining personal international health insurance that continues regardless of employment. The best choice depends on gap duration, your location, and healthcare needs.
      </p>

      <h3>I'm a visiting scholar—whose insurance covers me?</h3>
      <p>
        This depends on your arrangement. Some visiting positions include coverage from the host institution; others expect you to maintain home institution coverage; many provide nothing, leaving you to arrange your own. Clarify insurance provisions before accepting any visiting position.
      </p>

      <h3>Should I get personal international health insurance as an academic?</h3>
      <p>
        If you expect to move internationally multiple times, take extended research trips, or have gaps between positions, personal international coverage provides valuable continuity. It's an additional cost but eliminates transition stress and coverage gaps. For very stable positions with minimal international travel, institutional coverage may be sufficient.
      </p>

      <h3>My fellowship doesn't include health insurance—what do I do?</h3>
      <p>
        You need to arrange and budget for your own coverage. Options include your country's individual health insurance market, international health insurance (especially if you're abroad), or maintaining coverage through a spouse's plan if applicable. Factor the cost into your decision about accepting the fellowship.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I stay on my US university's health plan during an international sabbatical?</h3>
      <p>
        Check your university's policy. Some allow continuation during sabbatical with limited international coverage; others offer international provisions; some expect you to arrange your own coverage abroad. Even if your plan technically continues, verify it provides adequate coverage in your sabbatical country.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <section>
      <h2>Insurance for the Academic Journey</h2>
      <p>
        Academic careers are intellectually rewarding and geographically dynamic. The mobility that makes academic life rich also creates insurance complexity. But with planning, the challenges are manageable.
      </p>

      <p>
        The key principles: understand what your institutional coverage does and doesn't cover; plan for gaps and transitions before they happen; ensure coverage matches your research activities and locations; and consider personal international coverage for continuity through a mobile career.
      </p>

      <p>
        Your research takes you around the world. Your health insurance should follow—protecting you at conferences and in the field, during positions and between them, on sabbatical and at your home institution. With the right coverage, you can focus on what matters: the work.
      </p>
    </section>

  </article>
</PageShell>
